Normalization

internal/normalization/condition/mapper.go (eBay enum -> ConditionTier, keyword degredation)
internal/normalization/resolver/rules.go (MatchRule, NormalizeTitle(), Match())
internal/normalize/pipeline.go (Process(): conditionrules -> entity rules -> sidecar)
        Condition resolution runs first.
            step 1 - ebay enum map: hardcoded lookup table from condition/mapper.go
                if: raw condition string = "Very Good", ConditionVeryGood returns back immediaately, fast. If "damage" keyword, tier is downgraded by one step before returning.

                if: enum lookup fails, falls to sidecar's POST /classify  - receives title + raw condition string cat and returns 5 canonical labels
                        - with a confidence score
                        - if confidence score < 0.8 pipeline ignores ML result and falls to low conservative default rather than "low confidence guess"
        Entity Resolution runs second.
            step 1 is the rule matcher. canonical products have MatchRules with required keywords.
            if rules don't match it falls through to sidecar's POST /embed
                -sidecar embend normalize title with MiniLM-L6-v2 using cosin similiarity against embeddings for products in the catalog.
                    returns closest match and a confidence score between 0 and 1


        Pipeline bins score into three outcomes 0.85 resolves as ml confidence match
        0.75 >= 0.85 ml_low_confidence : coninical product ID is set but flagged for monitoring
        <0.75 : unresolved: listing is written to db but canonical_product_id is null - never scored or alerted on

        Condition is resolved first bc it affects pricing baseline will be compared against - condition wrong is worse than getting entity wrong.
        Misclassified condition dontition sends scoring stage to compare listing against WRONG population ofsold prices - GARBAGE deal if identity is correct

        Entity resolution is second bc - until you know what the product is, you can't look up pricing history....

        Rules run before sidecar in both cases because network cal to a local process costs time per listing. Sidecar only sees the shit rules can't handle.


